It's possible that the website you're trying to open in developer tools is blocking the default shortcut key combination (Ctrl + Shift + I) from being used. This blocking is usually done by adding an event listener to the keydown event and preventing the default behavior of the event.

One way to check if this is the case is to try opening the website in developer tools using a different shortcut key combination, such as F12 or Ctrl + Shift + C. If that works, then the issue is likely with the website blocking the default shortcut key combination.

If you need to open the website in developer tools frequently, you can try adding a custom shortcut key combination for opening developer tools that does not conflict with any other shortcuts on the website. This can be done by adding the following code to your userContent.css file:
```css
body {
  contextMenu: openDevTools;
}

@media screen and (hover: hover) {
  body {
    contextMenu: none;
  }
}

@media screen and (hover: none) {
  body {
    contextMenu: openDevTools;
  }
}

@media screen and (pointerevents: none) {
  body {
    contextMenu: openDevTools;
  }
}

@media screen and (-o-pointer-events: none) {
  body {
    contextMenu: openDevTools;
  }
}

@media screen and (-webkit-pointer-events: none) {
  body {
    contextMenu: openDevTools;
  }
}

@media (hover: none) {
  body {
    contextMenu: openDevTools;
  }
}
```
This code will add a custom context menu item for opening developer tools that will be available on the website regardless of whether the default shortcut key combination is blocked. The custom shortcut key combination can be set using the `openDevTools` keyword, which has a default value of `Ctrl + Shift + I`. You can change this value to a different shortcut key combination that is not blocked by the website.

TypeScript is a statically typed programming language that is a superset of JavaScript. It adds optional static typing and other features to the JavaScript language, such as classes, interfaces, and type annotations. TypeScript is designed to help developers catch errors early in the development process and make it easier to scale codebases.

Duck typing is a concept in dynamic programming languages, such as Python and JavaScript, that allows you to check if an object has a certain behavior without caring about its type. The name comes from the idea that if it looks like a duck, swims like a duck, and quacks like a duck, then it probably is a duck. In other words, if an object has the same methods and properties as another object, it can be used in place of that object, regardless of the object's type.

In TypeScript, duck typing is supported through the use of type inference, which allows the compiler to determine the types of variables based on how they are used. This means that you can use objects of different types as long as they have the same properties and methods.

For example, consider the following TypeScript code:
```typescript
class Duck {
  quack(): void {
    console.log('Quack!');
  }
}

class Chicken {
  cluck(): void {
    console.log('Cluck!');
  }
}

function quack(duck: object): void {
  duck.quack();
}

function cluck(chicken: object): void {
  chicken.cluck();
}

let duck = new Duck();
let chicken = new Chicken();

quack(duck);
cluck(chicken);
```
In this code, the `quack` and `cluck` functions take an object as an argument and call the `quack` and `cluck` methods on that object, respectively. The `duck` and `chicken` variables are both of type `object`, but the `duck` variable is an instance of the `Duck` class, while the `chicken` variable is an instance of the `Chicken` class.

When the `quack` function is called with the `duck` variable, it works because the `Duck` class has a `quack` method. When the `cluck` function is called with the `chicken` variable, it also works because the `Chicken` class has a `cluck` method.

This is an example of duck typing in TypeScript, where the type of the argument to the `quack` and `cluck` functions is inferred based on whether the object has the `quack` and `cluck` methods, respectively.

